If you try to access memory through a sad-face page directory entry, the CPU raises a page fault. 
Looking back at the original issue: The customer was reserving 100GB of address space. Each page table maps 512 Ã— 4KB = 2MB of address space, so thatâ€™s 51,200 page tables filled with sad faces. The memory manager optimizes this out and instead of creating 51,200 page tables filled with sad faces, it creates 51,200 page directory entries with sad faces. 
But wait, thatâ€™s still proportional to the size of the memory reserve, albeit with a much lower constant factor. How do we get the memory usage to be constant? 
Page directory entries are grouped together into page directories. Each page directory holds 512 page directory entries, and if the page directory is filled with sad faces, we can replace it with a sad face in the page directory pointer table. Our 51,200 sad-face page directory entries become 100 sad-face page directory pointer. (On x64, thereâ€™s another hierarchy level above the page directory pointer table, known as the page map level 4, but letâ€™s ignore that for now.) 
A reservation of 100GB of address space turns into this: 


